**Clinical Reasoning:**
While preoperative fasting is traditionally recommended to reduce aspiration risk, recent evidence supports minimal fasting—allowing clear fluids up to 2 hours before surgery—and even promoting carbohydrate loading to prevent catabolism and support recovery. Enhanced Recovery After Surgery (ERAS) protocols specifically emphasize shortening fasting durations and prioritizing early feeding to promote better outcomes. Therefore, strict preoperative fasting is neither universally necessary nor ideal in modern perioperative practices.

